&gt; Milt and Rich,
&gt; Later inlay is a case by case judgment.  Because the originality of the
tsuba is compromised, there will usually be a significant point reduction
for later inlay to a good, older iron plate.  If the inlay is extensive it
will probably fail.   If it is an attempt to &quot;convert&quot; the tsuba to a
different type (even if mumei), or is very crude or done after the Edo
period, it will fail.
&gt;
&gt; A hypothetical good Muromachi period Tosho guard with a subtle mon inlaid
during the Edo period would probably pass, but with a much lower point level
that the unaltered plate would have been awarded.  Also, if there is
significant alteration to the piece, the date given will be that of the
latest work.
&gt;
&gt; Most of the late gomoku zogan, mukade, etc., will fail for poor quality.
Maybe an exceptional example could pass, but I can&#39;t think of any examples.
Does anyone have one of these guards with an origami?
